[2] United Kingdom (England)
Date: Wed 25 May 2022 17:31 BST
Source: Daily Mail [abridged, edited]
https://www.dailymail.co.uk/health/article-10853975/England-records-SEVEN-cases-monkeypox-bringing-UK-total-78.html


England records 7 more cases of monkeypox bringing the UK total to 78
- The UK has logged 7 more monkeypox infections, all of which are in England, health chiefs said today [25 May 2022].
- The additional cases bring the UK total to 78 since the 1st in the current outbreak was publicised on 7 May [2022].
- It comes as experts warned scrapping smallpox vaccine scheme has left Britons vulnerable to monkeypox.
- Britons were routinely offered the smallpox jab until the 1970s, shortly after which the virus was eradicated.
- Waning immunity from family of viruses may explain why monkeypox outbreaks becoming more common.
- Although not made for monkeypox, Imvanex jab is up to 85% effective because the 2 viruses are so similar.

Another 7 monkeypox cases were logged in the UK today [25 May 2022] as the tropical virus usually only spotted in Africa continues to sweep the world. The new infections, all detected in England, bring Britain's total to 78 since the 1st case in the ongoing outbreak was publicised on 7 May [2022]. Scotland has so far logged one monkeypox case, while no infections have been reported in Wales or Northern Ireland.

Officials stated a 'notable proportion' have occurred among gay and bisexual men but have not provided an exact breakdown. No gender or age details have been shared, either.

UKHSA's chief medical adviser Dr Susan Hopkins said new monkeypox cases were being spotted 'promptly' due to 'extensive surveillance and contact tracing networks'.

[Byline: Emily Craig]

