[5] Canada (Ontario)
Date: Wed 25 May 2022 10:44 PM EDT
Source: Global News, The Canadian Press report [abridged, edited]
https://globalnews.ca/news/8868373/toronto-monkeypox-cases/


There are 2 new suspected cases of monkeypox and one probable case of the virus reported in Toronto on Wednesday [25 May 2022], bringing the total number of cases being investigated in the city to 4.

Toronto Public Health said all 3 of the newly reported cases are men -- 2 in their 30s and one in their 20s -- and they are "doing well."

One of the 3 men had traveled to Montreal and was a contact of the 1st suspected case Toronto Public Health said it was investigating in the city over the weekend [21-22 May 2022].

That 1st case involved a man in his 40s who had contact with someone who had recently travelled to Montreal. The agency said Wednesday [25 May 2022] that the 1st case was now considered a probable case.

In general, monkeypox does not spread easily between people and is transmitted through prolonged close contact, including direct contact with an infected person's respiratory droplets, bodily fluids, or sores.

Monkeypox is typically milder than smallpox and can cause fever, headache, muscle aches, exhaustion, swollen lymph nodes, and lesions all over the body.

Health officials have said the risk [to the public] posed by monkeypox is low.

